1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,409
In this video series we will go deep into mathematical logic to

2
00:00:03,509 --> 00:00:06,639
try and figure out what math is, and what it's limits are.

3
00:00:06,733 --> 00:00:10,469
For much of history math was essentially geometry, in the sense that

4
00:00:10,569 --> 00:00:14,417
everything we proved was grounded in some form of geometric intuition.

5
00:00:14,466 --> 00:00:17,821
Its not hard to imagine triangles, squares and circles, and as

6
00:00:17,921 --> 00:00:20,830
we start to study them, we can start to notice certain

7
00:00:20,930 --> 00:00:24,452
patterns, find different ways classify the shapes and we can find

8
00:00:24,552 --> 00:00:28,185
certain surprising relations between different shapes. For example,

9
00:00:28,266 --> 00:00:32,181
we can prove that the sum of the inner angles of any triangle

10
00:00:32,281 --> 00:00:36,656
is exactly 180 degrees by drawing a parallel line at its top vertex.

11
00:00:36,733 --> 00:00:40,414
The world of geometry is natural and intuitive. However, as

12
00:00:40,514 --> 00:00:44,835
math developed, it has become further abstracted from our intuitions.

13
00:00:44,933 --> 00:00:49,565
By allowing more abstract ideas --such as infinity methods-- into mathematics

14
00:00:49,665 --> 00:00:53,376
allows us to broaden the mathematical universe but it comes at

15
00:00:53,476 --> 00:00:56,818
the cost of making math harder to wrap our heads around.

16
00:00:56,918 --> 00:00:59,768
I will soon make a whole video on the history of

17
00:00:59,868 --> 00:01:02,718
math. For now I will just say that in the 1800's

18
00:01:02,818 --> 00:01:06,959
mathematics had developed far beyond the intuitive realm of geometry.

19
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,672
Calculus had been developed which accepted the idea

20
00:01:09,772 --> 00:01:12,879
of points at infinity, algebra had developed significantly,

21
00:01:12,979 --> 00:01:15,271
and many had started to accept the existence

22
00:01:15,371 --> 00:01:18,315
of imaginary numbers as legitimate mathematical objects.

23
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:21,754
However, math had branched out in so many different ways

24
00:01:21,854 --> 00:01:25,517
that there was no longer a common foundation for mathematics.

25
00:01:25,617 --> 00:01:28,910
In the 1800's people --such as Frege, Peano Russell and

26
00:01:29,010 --> 00:01:32,118
others-- started to ground mathematics in the logic.

27
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:35,650
To understand this, let us return to the easy stuff and

28
00:01:35,750 --> 00:01:38,942
consider 1 plus 2 equals 3. When viewed in one way,

29
00:01:39,042 --> 00:01:42,104
this is just an arbitrary string of five symbols.

30
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:45,509
It get's its meaning when interpreted in a structure like the

31
00:01:45,609 --> 00:01:49,309
natural number line, where the numbers get interpreted as we expect.

32
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:52,103
The plus sign can be interpreted as a function

33
00:01:52,203 --> 00:01:55,029
--which we can see as a computer program-- which

34
00:01:55,129 --> 00:01:58,077
takes in two inputs and has a well-defined output.

35
00:01:58,133 --> 00:02:02,399
The equality symbol just checks that the two sides of the equation map to

36
00:02:02,499 --> 00:02:06,288
this same element in the line, so we say that the equation holds.

37
00:02:07,333 --> 00:02:10,352
Now, if we consider a more complicated equation such as Euler's

38
00:02:10,452 --> 00:02:13,571
identity, we see that this equation is meaningless in the natural

39
00:02:13,671 --> 00:02:17,136
number line, since the intended interpretations of each of the constants

40
00:02:17,236 --> 00:02:19,563
involved do not exist in the natural number line.

41
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:22,127
To understand this equation, we require a more

42
00:02:22,227 --> 00:02:24,698
complex structure known as the complex plane.

43
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:27,749
However, once we have done this, we can evaluate it in

44
00:02:27,849 --> 00:02:30,120
the same way as 1 plus 2 equals 3. We just

45
00:02:30,220 --> 00:02:33,790
have map the constants to their representations in the structure,

46
00:02:33,866 --> 00:02:37,101
and then perform the complex exponentiations function, and we can observe

47
00:02:37,201 --> 00:02:39,659
that the left side hand side evaluates to the same point

48
00:02:39,759 --> 00:02:42,491
in the structure as the interpretation of the right hand side.

49
00:02:43,533 --> 00:02:46,489
3 Blue 1 Brown made an excellent video explaining why

50
00:02:46,589 --> 00:02:49,833
this equality holds --you can check that video out here--.

51
00:02:50,933 --> 00:02:53,188
But from the point of view of a logician,

52
00:02:53,288 --> 00:02:56,289
both of these formulas are the simplest possible. They

53
00:02:56,389 --> 00:02:58,931
are at the bottom of the complexity hierarchy.

54
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,223
We can create more complicated formulas using quantifiers. For example,

55
00:03:03,323 --> 00:03:06,634
consider this equation, which states that the sum of the

56
00:03:06,734 --> 00:03:09,192
first n odd numbers is equal to n-squared.

57
00:03:09,266 --> 00:03:12,762
Meaning that 1 plus 3 plus 5 plus dot dot dot n-times, then

58
00:03:12,862 --> 00:03:16,602
it is equal to n squared. This is some random pattern which one

59
00:03:16,702 --> 00:03:21,052
notices if one looks for patterns in the natural numbers for long enough.

60
00:03:21,133 --> 00:03:23,433
We can convince ourselves that it is true

61
00:03:23,533 --> 00:03:25,892
by going through each possible value of n.

62
00:03:25,933 --> 00:03:28,001
Since one is equal to 1 square.

63
00:03:28,600 --> 00:03:30,615
1 plus 3 is equal to 2 squared,

64
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:34,940
1 plus 3 plus 5 is equal to 3 squared etc.

65
00:03:35,533 --> 00:03:38,888
It seems to always hold, but how do we know that there is

66
00:03:38,988 --> 00:03:43,191
not some weird number, just beyond our grasp which breaks this pattern?

67
00:03:43,266 --> 00:03:47,138
Well, to evaluate a formula such as this one, we use the principle

68
00:03:47,238 --> 00:03:51,652
of mathematical induction, which just means that we check that it holds for

69
00:03:51,752 --> 00:03:54,901
n equals 1, and check that if it holds for n equals k,

70
00:03:55,001 --> 00:03:57,429
then it also applies to n equals k plus 1.

71
00:03:58,466 --> 00:04:01,628
This can be seen using dominoes, if we know that we will

72
00:04:01,728 --> 00:04:05,240
push the first domino, and we know that once any domino falls,

73
00:04:05,340 --> 00:04:08,676
it will knock over the next domino, then we know that every

74
00:04:08,776 --> 00:04:12,812
domino will eventually fall, even if there are infinitely many of them.

75
00:04:12,866 --> 00:04:16,238
So, we see that by adding quantifiers into our logic, and by

76
00:04:16,338 --> 00:04:20,809
accepting mathematical induction, we can prove things about every element in an

77
00:04:20,909 --> 00:04:24,917
infinite structure, using finitely many symbols. But what do we mean by

78
00:04:25,017 --> 00:04:28,562
prove? There turn out to be two very different ways of defining

79
00:04:28,662 --> 00:04:33,770
a mathematical proof --and therefore of defining mathematical truth-- and the relationship

80
00:04:33,870 --> 00:04:36,720
between them is at the heart of mathematical logic.

